{{infobox historic site | name = Agave Landscape and Ancient Industrial Facilities of Tequila | image = Campo y cerro.jpg | caption = Agave field near Tequila, Jalisco | coordinates = {{coord|20.8595|-103.7666|display=inline,title}} | location = Valles Region, [[Jalisco]] | designation1 = WHS | designation1_date = 2006 <small>(30th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small> | designation1_type = Cultural | designation1_criteria = ii, iv, v, vi | designation1_number = [http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1209 1209] | designation1_free1name = State Party | designation1_free1value = Mexico | designation1_free2name = Region | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Americas|Latin America and the Caribbean]] }} The '''Agave Landscape and Ancient Industrial Facilities of Tequila''' is a cultural [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] in [[Mexico]].<ref name="UNESCO">{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1209 |title= Agave Landscape and Ancient Industrial Facilities of Tequila |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> The 35,019-hectare site is part of an expansive landscape of [[blue agave]], shaped by the culture of the plant used since the 16th century to produce the spirit known as [[tequila]] and for at least two millennia to make fermented drinks (such as [[pulque]]) and cloth.<ref name="UNESCO"/> Within the landscape are working distilleries reflecting the growth in the consumption of tequila in the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name="UNESCO"/> Today, this agave culture is seen as part of Mexican [[national identity]].<ref name="UNESCO"/> The Tequila landscape has contributed to many works of art such as film, music, dance, and paintings. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1209|title=Agave Landscape and Ancient Industrial Facilities of Tequila|last=|first=|date=|website=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref>
The site includes the living, working agave fields and the urban settlements of [[Tequila, Jalisco|Tequila]], [[Magdalena Municipality, Jalisco|Magdalena]], [[El Arenal, Jalisco|El Arenal]] and [[Amatitan]].<ref name="UNESCO"/> The area is also testimony to the [[Teuchitlan tradition]] (AD 200-900) which shaped the landscape through the creation of terraces for agriculture, housing, temples, ceremonial mounds and [[Mesoamerican ball game|ball courts]].<ref name="UNESCO"/>
